<@U575ZG9U2> Also,  pretty sure that <@U56CXCTGA>  is right, you shouldn’t be re-declaring your variables with “var” inside your function.

<@U575ZG9U2> my hunch is that, specifically, the “y=NaN” is coming from the fact that you used  “var y = Number(y);” to define y within the function.  Whereas you used “var x = Number(arr[0]);” to define x within the function.  When you call the function, you only gave it the array [1, 2, 3, 4], so without calling on that array, like you did for x, y remains undefined and therefore, when you use the Number() function, it returns NaN.  That’s my guess anyways.

<@U575ZG9U2> Because you are declaring both x and y again within your function, they are being treated as local variables within the function. If you want a more consistent behavior, move your var x and var y declarations into your function, or remove the var keyword on them within your function. 
Check out the second example here for more detail: <https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/scripting/javascript/advanced/variable-scope-javascript>

I was looking at the homework for tonight and it looks like there is an error in one of the equations. 
The provided equation is: 
var cakesWeCanBake = (bakers * cakeBakingTime) * hoursLeftUntilParty; 
This will work but only if the cakeBakingTime is 1 hour. Any other value will break this.

The actual equation should be something like: 
cakesBaked = (numBakers * Math.floor((hoursTillParty / cakeBakingTime)));
Though if you use this equation you won't pass the check during submission.
